Below is a complete, self-contained HTML file that meets your requirements. This file includes:

- A `<textarea>` for pasting CSV data.
- A button that, when clicked, parses the CSV data into a table.
- JavaScript to handle:
  - Quoted fields containing commas (e.g., `"Smith, John"` will be treated as a single field).
  - Escaped quotes within fields (e.g., `"He said, ""Hello""."` will be parsed correctly as `He said, "Hello".`).
  - Varying column counts across rows (each row will be displayed with as many columns as it has, without errors).
- CSS for styling the table with:
  - Alternating row colors (e.g., even rows in light gray, odd rows in white).
  - Clear borders around the table and cells.

The JavaScript uses a custom CSV parser to accurately handle the edge cases you mentioned. It splits the input into rows and fields while respecting CSV rules, then generates an HTML table dynamically.

Here's the full HTML file. You can copy and paste it into a text editor, save it with a `.html` extension (e.g., `csv_parser.html`), and open it in a web browser to test it.

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>CSV Parser</title>
    <style>
        /* Table styling */
        table {
            border-collapse: collapse; /* Merge borders for a clean look */
            width: 100%; /* Make the table full width */
            margin-top: 20px; /* Add some space above the table */
        }

        th, td {
            border: 1px solid #000; /* Clear black borders */
            padding: 8px; /* Padding for readability */
            text-align: left; /* Left-align text */
        }

        tr:nth-child(even) { /* Alternating row colors */
            background-color: #f2f2f2; /* Light gray for even rows */
        }

        tr:nth-child(odd) {
            background-color: #ffffff; /* White for odd rows */
        }

        /* General styling for the page */
        body {
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif; /* Clean font */
            margin: 20px; /* Margin around the body */
        }

        textarea {
            width: 100%; /* Full width */
            height: 200px; /* Fixed height for better usability */
            margin-bottom: 10px; /* Space below textarea */
        }

        button {
            padding: 10px 15px; /* Padding for button */
            background-color: #4CAF50; /* Green background */
            color: white; /* White text */
            border: none; /* No border */
            cursor: pointer; /* Pointer cursor on hover */
        }

        button:hover {
            background-color: #45a049; /* Darker green on hover */
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <h1>CSV Parser</h1>
    <p>Paste your CSV data into the textarea below and click the button to parse it into a table.</p>

    <textarea id="csvInput" placeholder='Example:
"Name","Age","City"
"John, Doe",30,"New York"
"Jane ""The Great"" Smith",25,"San Francisco"
Another,Row,With,Extra,Columns
A,Row,With,Fewer'></textarea>

    <button id="parseButton">Parse CSV</button>

    <div id="tableOutput"></div> <!-- This is where the table will be inserted -->

    <script>
        // Function to escape HTML to prevent XSS
        function escapeHTML(str) {
            if (!str) return '';
            return str
                .replace(/&/g, '&amp;')
                .replace(/</g, '&lt;')
                .replace(/>/g, '&gt;')
                .replace(/"/g, '&quot;')
                .replace(/'/g, '&#039;');
        }

        // Function to parse CSV string
        function parseCSV(csvString) {
            const lines = csvString.trim().split('\n'); // Split into rows
            const result = [];

            for (const line of lines) {
                const fields = [];
                let field = '';
                let inQuotes = false;

                for (let i = 0; i < line.length; i++) {
                    const char = line[i];

                    if (char === '"') {
                        // Handle quotes
                        if (inQuotes && line[i + 1] === '"') {
                            // Escaped quote (e.g., "")
                            field += '"'; // Add a single quote
                            i++; // Skip the next quote
                        } else {
                            // Toggle inQuotes
                            inQuotes = !inQuotes;
                        }
                    } else if (char === ',' && !inQuotes) {
                        // End of field
                        fields.push(field.trim()); // Add the field and trim whitespace
                        field = '';
                    } else {
                        // Add the character to the current field
                        field += char;
                    }
                }

                // Add the last field
                if (field.trim() !== '') {
                    fields.push(field.trim());
                }

                result.push(fields); // Add the row to the result
            }

            return result; // Return the parsed data as an array of arrays
        }

        // Function to generate HTML table from parsed data
        function generateTable(data) {
            if (data.length === 0) return '<p>No data to display.</p>'; // Handle empty input

            let tableHTML = '<table>';

            for (let i = 0; i < data.length; i++) {
                tableHTML += '<tr>'; // Start a new row

                for (let j = 0; j < data[i].length; j++) {
                    const cellContent = escapeHTML(data[i][j]); // Escape for safety
                    if (i === 0) {
                        // Treat the first row as headers
                        tableHTML += `<th>${cellContent}</th>`;
                    } else {
                        tableHTML += `<td>${cellContent}</td>`;
                    }
                }

                tableHTML += '</tr>'; // End the row
            }

            tableHTML += '</table>';
            return tableHTML;
        }

        // Add event listener to the button
        document.getElementById('parseButton').addEventListener('click', function() {
            const csvText = document.getElementById('csvInput').value; // Get textarea value
            const parsedData = parseCSV(csvText); // Parse the CSV
            const tableHTML = generateTable(parsedData); // Generate the table HTML
            document.getElementById('tableOutput').innerHTML = tableHTML; // Insert into the page
        });
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

### How It Works:
1. **Input Handling**: Paste your CSV data into the textarea. For example:
   ```
   "Name","Age","City"
   "John, Doe",30,"New York"
   "Jane ""The Great"" Smith",25,"San Francisco"
   Another,Row,With,Extra,Columns
   A,Row,With,Fewer
   ```
   This will correctly parse:
   - `"John, Doe"` as a single field.
   - `"Jane ""The Great"" Smith"` as `Jane "The Great" Smith`.
   - Rows with different column counts (e.g., the last two rows).

2. **Button Action**: Clicking the button triggers the JavaScript, which:
   - Parses the CSV using the `parseCSV` function.
   - Generates a table using the `generateTable` function.
   - Inserts the table into the `<div id="tableOutput">`.

3. **Edge Cases Handled**:
   - **Quoted fields with commas**: Treated as single fields.
   - **Escaped quotes**: Properly unescaped (e.g., `""` becomes `"`).
   - **Varying column counts**: Each row is processed independently, so rows with fewer or more columns are displayed as-is.
   - **Empty lines or rows**: Ignored or handled gracefully.

4. **Styling**: The table uses CSS for alternating rows and borders. You can tweak the styles in the `<style>` section if needed.

